data.name: txtRefreshInterval.ToolTip
data.value:
Program main tick interval in milliseconds. Every refresh cycle: - program first analyse serial data buffer - make all sensors calculations - stores data to files - visualizes all data, refreshes charts - send all needed data to internet (takes into account settings "send data to ... every ... sec").
Generally it should be around Arduino sensor measurement cycle (can me measured manually watching serial log output). If it would be too small, this will make unproductive CPU load and leads to dublicate data. If too large, intermediate data will be lost.

data.name: txtMaxLogWindowLines.ToolTip
data.value:
Max number of lines displayed in a log window. Full log can be seen in serial log file (see above). Too large numbers will lead to memory consumption.
Default 500 lines.

data.name: txtMaxPoints.ToolTip
data.value:
Max number of points displaying on charts. Too big values will leed to large memory consumption.
As a hint - new point is added every main tick interval. So if you want to see last 24h on your graphs, and have 10 sec main tick interval set, you should use 8630 points

data.name: label21.ToolTip
data.value:
Calibration value for zero wind speed
Stop wind speed sensor and enter value which would lead to 0 speed value. Default 83, may be different for different sensors

data.name: txtWSpeedZero.ToolTip
data.value:
Calibrating wind speed zero speed value
To measure it, stop wind sensor rotation and look for [WnV] value in Serial Log Window. Note, that it can't be 0. If it is 0, then something wrong with the sensor
Default value (suits for my conditions) 83 units

data.name: txtWindyLimit.ToolTip

data.name: cmbWetMode.ToolTip
data.value: Which sensor program should use to measure rain condition if more then one present (wet sensor and optical rain gauge counter) If you have two of them - use "Both" unless you face problems

data.name: txtWetLimit.ToolTip
data.value:
Wet threshold limit. All values higher then this will be treated as a dry condition
IMPORTANT. Because when Boltwood Rain Condition is signaling "Wet", software like CCDAutopilot or CCDCommander could stop imaging run, "Wet" signal is never set up during Sky Clear condition (remains "Dry").

data.name: txtGaugeInc.ToolTip
data.value:
All time RG-11 rain counter incremental value.
It used by narodmon to display rain intensity.
Can be manually set to any value by entering it here and pressing "Set" button

data.name: txtRGScale.ToolTip
data.value:
Conversion multiplier to convert from RG-11 counter to mm of percipitation
Should correspond to RG-11 hardware switch settings (can be 0.2 mm, 0.01 mm, 0.001 mm, 0.01", 0.001", 0.0001")
Recomended 0.01mm

data.name: txtRainLimit.ToolTip
data.value: Rain threshold limit. All values higher then this will be treated as a wet condition, and lower as a rain condition

data.name: txtCloudysky.ToolTip
data.value: Cloudy sky threshold limit. All values higher then this will be treated as a cloudy sky and lower - as a very cloudy

data.name: txtClearsky.ToolTip
data.value: Clear sky threshold limit. All values higher then this will be treated as a clear sky

data.name: txtCSHeaterPauseTime.ToolTip
data.value: Interval between two autoheating cycles, seconds

data.name: txtCSDecreasingMaxDelta.ToolTip
data.value:
Very advanced settings :) Do not change it untill you know what you are doing
Program determines when Cloud Sensor need heating based on some conditions: - CS value is in "CS threshold switching on" interval (see above) - average CS value for every 5 minutes are decreasing and the decriments are in "CS decreasing thershold" interval - Since previous heating passed more "Heater pause time" seconds - There is no rain now - There is 100% humidity - It is dark now
